<p>
Whether we like it or not, food holds a grip on our lives unlike anything else. Sustenance is required for us to survive, and no matter how strict the diet, everyone must make decisions on what it is that they will eat that day. Somehow, humans must choose from the seemingly infinite number of options that flood the food industry on a daily basis. Moreover, it’s not just about what tastes good, food now comes with baggage—or hidden attachments—making our decision even more complicated. In fact, it’s very rare today to talk about food on a global scale without a crisis being affixed to it. Between global health, ethical production methods, youth wellbeing, sustainable farming, and more, it’s easy to see that what you eat signifies more than just calories. Mixed within all of this exists corporations whose goals often start and end with profit, creating an environment built around cheap production and positive consumer feedback. However, several contradictions exist among mass-produced food products where what is good for individual health and the environment is rarely what is cheap to produce. Further, these conflicts between health and economics are skewed more when considering the impacts of marketing, government lobbying, and cultural norms. Finally, there seems to be an overwhelming stress on advertising to a younger audience, thus exploiting a demographic both unequipped to combat the  highly impressionable strategies of food brands. The intersection of these areas create a dynamic within the food industry that is both unhealthy and unsustainable for the world, yet changing them remains difficult as foods’ ability to continually draw us in is more powerful than ever. 
</p>

<p>
The food industry is unquestionably one of the largest in the world. According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, the foodservice and food retailing industries supplied about $1.79 trillion worth of food in 2019. (Zeballos, 2007) This doesn’t seem to be changing soon either, from 2016-2020 there were over 20,000 new food related products introduced to stores each of those years suggesting that demand is remaining high for new products and new ways to spend money. (Dong, 2021)  Thinking of the food industry as a business makes a lot of sense, but the ramifications of this are just as prominent. There are very few industries that have the kind of ‘constant demand’ that food does, but where this money comes from is an important question. One of the main things to consider is how affordable different foods are to the average consumer, as the logical conclusion is that cheaper food will be bought more often. The figure to the right  shows the price fluctuations with respect to inflation for various categories of food from 1985 to 2000. The studies cited in (Walinga, 2009)  shows that foods like fruits and vegetables which “aid in managing body weight… and reduce the risk of cancer” have drastically increased in price. In stark contrast to these healthier foods, the nutrient-poor foods like “Sugars & sweets”, “Carbonated soft drinks” or “Fats & oils” all are more accessible and affordable to the public in respect to price. This standard that the food industry set in which highly processed foods are affordable for the public set a precedent of overconsumption on these fattier, more sugary, and high caloric foods. This is emphasized by Americans who spent over $970 Billion on food-away-from-home spending in 2019  (Anikka, 2022) likely because of their cheap prices and high caloric meals. Since fast food companies and the foods they represent are able to keep their prices so much lower than that of healthier options, their ability to convince consumers is far greater than anyone else. This context is important to understand as we dive further into what strategies companies use to get people to buy their products. 
</p>

<p>
We have established the large presence of foods with higher sugar and caloric levels within the food industry, but this is also what makes up a large portion of the advertising within American news outlets. Consider the most important television advertising day of the year, the Super Bowl. During 2012-2014, food and beverage ads made up over 26% of all advertisements (of any genre) during that period of time with the majority of these relating to unhealthy foods, fast food, or sugary drinks. (Lydecker, 2017) Why is it that these are the images and videos that we are flooded with so aggressively? Conversely, why is this not reciprocated on the other end of the spectrum with the likes of healthy foods or those that are beneficial towards a healthy lifestyle. Advertising is incredibly effective towards these less healthy options, it’s important to consider whether this would work towards other products. 
</p>

<p>
Take the advertising ploy of Got Milk? as an example of the power of advertising. “Beginning in earnest after World War II, the US government, schools, and doctors had all promoted milk as a nutritious drink, a necessary component of a healthy diet. By the 1950s, milk had assumed an important role in what people thought was a normal, nutritious lifestyle. In the United States then, milk had been a family staple.” (Ng et al., 2009) This provides a simple case of promoting a narrative surrounding a product creating a very long lasting reputation towards a product. In fact, they did it as a way to directly combat the likes of soda brands and other drinks that were looking to take over the youthful advertising market. The issue of selling milk is that it is boring and not nearly as attractive as other food products, despite the potential for being a very healthy drink alternative. However, through a deliberate advertising effort milk created a brand for itself by using many of the same frameworks that are used for less healthy options.  
</p>




