<summary>Food For Thought by Henry Howell</summary>

<p>
We all have to eat food, it’s necessary to sustain life. Many things that are necessary to life are fairly straightforward; breathing, drinking water, etc. So why is figuring out what to eat so hard these days?? Food For Thought is a game that takes you through a day in the life of a high school student and just trying to get through the day. While attempting to pick out foods to eat, you are bombarded with advertisements of all kinds. Eventually it gets to the point where it’s almost impossible to do anything without feeling the overwhelming weight of advertisements. Ultimately you get to see the effects that not just having to eat sugary foods, but also having to deal with the advertisements that you see on any given day have on your overall health. 
</p>

<p>
The goal was to not only emphasize that there are bad food options out there, but also poor strategies of getting people to eat them. Most of the time we are just broken down until we give in eventually. Furthermore, I wanted to use a high school student to show that children and teenagers are attacked more intensely as that group of “customers” are more impressionable to companies. There are certainly ethical ramifications to these that this game doesn’t touch on explicitly but that I wanted to have underlying tones throughout. 
</p>

<p>
Finally, one of the most important aspects of the game is the health bar that features on every page. To be able to see how you’re “feeling” after every given decision you make helps you think more clearly about what you’re putting in your body as well as how you’re treating it. This is one of the benefits of playing games, allowing us to pick up on things we might be taking for granted in our own lives. I want people to think about what if they had a health bar constantly following them around as they went through their day and how it would affect their decisions. More specifically, what would be more convincing to yourself; your own health or the advertisers. Food presented an excellent crossroads to look at several different aspects of our lives that force us to consider and think more deeply about. So play Food For Thought!
</p>

