<p>
The food industry relies on two main persuasion frameworks in order to be successful; social proof and attention. Social proof works off of everyone’s need to fit in with what the people around them are doing while attention assumes people will give more importance to the things they casually focus on more often. (Bragdon, 2017) These two frameworks can summarize the goals of nearly every food advertisement out there. Take McDonald’s for example, the gaudy golden arches not only draw your immediate attention in, but also boast the slogan “Billions and Billions Served” suggesting that your choice to eat there is being backed up by billions of people before you, so it must be the right thing to do. One of the most prominent ways in which advertisers maintain a firm grip on their audience is through their targeting of a younger audience.
</p>

<p>
Children are vulnerable when it comes to the many different techniques that food companies use in order to draw them in. Famously in 2011, McDonald’s CEO Jim Skinner claimed that “Ronald McDonald does not advertise unhealthy food to children. We provide many choices that fit with the balanced, active lifestyle. It is up to them to choose and their parents to choose, and it is their responsibility to do so.” (Mallarino et al., 2013) Yes, McDonald’s does offer options that when balanced could fit into a lifestyle that is more healthy than not, but will kids know the intricacies that go into this tightrope walk of healthy living? According to a study run in 2012, around 60-90% of food marketing directed towards children was for pre-sugared breakfast cereals, soft drinks, savory snacks, confectionery and fast foods. (Cairns et al., 2013) Additionally, a study where children wore cameras as a way to see what forms of advertisements they were exposed to the most showed that children interacted with what they called non-core foods 27.3 times a day and core foods only 12.3. (Signal et al., 2017) Once again, the existence of these products do not immediately suggest the presence of unhealthiness in the United States or worldwide, but their constant marketing to the public puts everyone at a distinct disadvantage healthwise. Furthermore, if this is the culture that children are raised in, what are we as a society supposed to expect from them when they grow older? 
</p>

<p>
There are efforts to limit marketing directed at children, but it seems like a much more effective strategy would be to shift the content that children are being exposed to. One way this is being accomplished is through the Children’s Food and Beverage Advertising Initiative. (BBBPrograms, 2022) Their main goal is based around their four pillars of: broad industry representation, extensive media coverage, strict uniform nutrition criteria, and strong compliance oversight. Their goal is simply to convince advertisers to limit the presence of foods with  added sugars or sodium and instead include “more food groups or important nutrients like calcium and Vitamin D in foods advertised to children.” (BBBPrograms, 2022) This is a clear example of a large national program taking action to not only combat the state of the food industry, but to also use persuasion architecture to change the system for the better. 
</p>

<p>
The ways in which these frameworks are used within healthy food advertising are unique. One study from mdpi (Roose and Mulier, 2020) looked at the way in which healthy foods are advertised as a way of citing the differences between healthy and unhealthy foods, why one is more successful and what’s at the root of that. They specifically looked at sensory advertising, meaning what senses that advertisements attempt to target when advertising. They found that when healthy food ads target only a singular sense (verbal or visual in this case), they are far more successful than if they attempt to target both. It seems as though people can suss out when they are trying to be overly convinced of something good. Tipping the scales towards overtly overdramatizing a product’s positive characteristics can at times be counterproductive as people see through the veil to the perhaps less enticing aspects of healthy foods. Essentially, they found that “the healthy single-sense ads evoke fewer negative thoughts than the healthy multiple-sense visual ad” as can be seen in the figure above. (Roose and Mulier, 2020) It’s the masking of the product in some way that defines healthy advertising. Another study shows this in another way, “healthier foods are not as widely or consistently available as less healthful foods. The fact that convenience stores are so easily accessible makes them an important part of the adolescent food environment. Knowledge of which foods are available is important for research, education, and health promotion.” (Gebauer, 2011) Not only does there need to be creative advertising but there also needs to be a way for people to access the food in question. Putting  healthier foods away from the door subconsciously creates the connection in customers’ heads that they are worse products. The food right next to the cashier doesn't carry added benefits, they simply are more convenient. Once again it seems as though smarter persuasion strategies, such as social proof and attention, could be used towards making healthier foods more appealing to the consumer. 
</p>

<p>
It’s important to note that the difference between healthy and unhealthy foods is not exactly binary. In fact it will likely remain a heavily contested question within the food industry and rather than contest that, this paper sought to identify some underlying pieces of food advertising and what can be learned from them. Advertisements represent the persuasion architectures used towards convincing consumers to buy certain products and, as this paper has established, most often those products are associated with unhealthy lifestyles. There is certainly room within this field for the likes of healthier food companies to grow their advertising brand, as can be seen in the example of Got Milk. Furthermore, the impressionable nature of children to food advertisements is quite large and fast food brands and unhealthy food companies alike have largely been exploiting this. However, this is starting to change as nonprofits and government agencies look to limit television advertising towards children and shift the narrative towards more nutritious goods. Overall, asking the food industry to holistically shift to healthier practices is impractical, but there is a lot to be learned from the existing strategies and how they can be applied to healthier products.
</p>









